Cerebral circulation revisited: an historical essay. Three centuries of investigations relevant to cerebral circulation, from the discoveries of circulation by Harvey (1628) and Willis (1664) to the 2-deoxyglucose methods of Sokoloff (1977), have been surveyed. Perspective is provided from discussion of such developments as: the discovery of oxygen and its role in combustion, respiration and cellular metabolism recognition of the blood-brain barrier especially as selective exchange transport systems